1. Introduction

  • Principal Component Analysis (PCA) is a dimensionality reduction technique used to transform a high dimensional data set into data of lesser dimensions while minimizing the loss of information Gatto (2023b).

  • The goal of PCA is to reduce the number of dimensions in a way that the new data remains useful Gatto (2023a).

  • Principal components are uncorrelated and explain the variation in the data Sanchez (2012).

  • For this activity, we want to investigate if the patterns of mutation frequencies are similar across all different countries for which we have calculated the mutation frequency.

    • We are interested in finding out which regions have similar mutation frequency patterns.
      • If two regions have similar mutation frequencies, they may need to enter lock-down together.

  • This activity is based on the article of Keita (2023).

Principal Component Analysis (PCA). Figure from All (n.d.).

Question

  • Which mutation pattern (frequency) or the mutation pattern of which region contributes the most to the viral evolution success?
    • Performing a PCA analysis is to find which variable contributes the most to the variation or variability observed in the data.
      • The data is organized such that regions are in columns and SNP mutations are in lines.

2. Load and Pre-Process Data

2.1. Load libraries

library("corrr")
library("ggcorrplot")
library("FactoMineR")

2.2. Read the COVID-19 Frequency Table data

  • Read file and transform into matrix.
heatmap_table <- read.table("./data/temp_file.txt", row.names = 1, header = TRUE, sep = "\t")
heatmap_table = as.matrix(heatmap_table)

2.3. Apply normalization methods

2.3.1. Log-transformation

  • We used this method with in the hierarchical clustering analysis.
log_table_09_18_2020 = log (heatmap_table + 1)
  • You can use the View() function to compare the heatmap_table object to the log-normalized object log_table_09_18_2020

2.3.2. Normalization using the scale() function

  • The scale() function centers and/or scales the columns of a numeric matrix

  • Check the ?scale() command in the terminal

covid19_normalized <- scale(log_table_09_18_2020)
  • Use the View() function to compare the heatmap_table object to the covid19_normalized object

3. Correlation matrix and Principal Components

3.1 Compute matrix

corr_matrix_covid19 <- cor(covid19_normalized)

  • After computing the correlation matrix, take a look at it using the View() function

  • Finally, visualize the correlation matrix using the ggcorrplot() function:

ggcorrplot(corr_matrix_covid19)

  • The higher the value, the most positively correlated two variables are;

  • The closer the value is to -1, the most negatively correlated the variables are.

  • Notice that the values in the diagonal are all 1s (ones), in the table and in the figure, showing that the vector of each country has 100% correlation with itself.

  • Notice that pangolin and bat are highly related to each other. Therefore we could make these samples a single group or cluster.

3.2. Apply PCA

  • Use the princomp() function to perform principal component analysis on numeric data matrix
data.pca.covid19 <- princomp(corr_matrix_covid19)

3.3. R PCA summary

summary(data.pca.covid19)

  • We notice that 21 principal components have been generated (Comp. 1 to Comp. 21).

  • Each component explains a percentage of the total variance in the dataset.

  • Observe in the Cumulative Proportion section that principal component 1 explains 80.5% of the total variance.

  • The cumulative proportion of PC1 and PC2 explains more than 94% of the total variance.

  • As an implication, PC1 and PC2 accurately represent the data.

  • We can proceed to visualize the variation of the data on the PC1 and PC2 axis.

3.4. Loadings of Principal Components PC1 and PC2

data.pca.covid19$loadings[,1:2]

  • The loading matrix shows PC1 with high values for Bat, Pangolin, China and Australia.

  • For USA, Brazil, Italy, Germany and Canada for instance, the PC1 values are negative.

  • This suggests that COVID-19 samples with frequencies similar to original bat and pangolin infection are in deficit while countries with different frequencies are in excess.

  • For PC2, a pattern is not clear except for a correlation to the latitude of the mutation frequencies.

    • Australia is on the global south, as is Brazil, but PC2 is negative for Australia but positive for Brazil.
    • If we consider the traffic between countries, PC2 may explain proximity of Italy and Germany and Italy and Brazil.
    • The first COVID-19 case in Brazil was imported from Italy.

4. Visualization of the Principal Components

  • The previous visualization gave a good understanding of the relationship between each of the first two principal components and attributes in the data.

  • However, this does not help visualization.

  • In this part we will generate visualization of the principal components.

4.1. Scree Plot

  • The first visualization approach is the scree plot.

  • The scree plot is used to visualize the importance of each Principal Component in accounting for variability present in the data.

  • This graph can be used to determine the number of PC to retain that explain the variability present in the data Wikipedia (n.d.).

  • We load the R package factoextra, because we will use a function from this package.

library(factoextra)
## Welcome! Want to learn more? See two factoextra-related books at https://goo.gl/ve3WBa
  • The function we need to use is fviz_eig(); in the console you can type ?fviz_eig() to obtain more information about this function.
fviz_eig(data.pca.covid19)

  • Now we will add the addlabels parameters set to TRUE.
fviz_eig(data.pca.covid19, addlabels = TRUE)

  • This plot shows the eigenvalues in a downward curve, from highest to lowest.

  • More than 94% of variation is explained by PC1 and PC2.

4.2. BiPlot of the attributes

  • BiPlots are used to show similarities and dissimilarities between the samples.

  • BiPlots show the impact of each attribute (country) on each of the principal components

fviz_pca_var(data.pca.covid19, col.var = "black")

  • Conclusions from the BiPlot figure
    • Variables grouped together are positively related to each other
    • The higher the distance from the origin, the better represented the variable is
    • Variables negatively correlate
  • For the sake of simplicity, lets assume PC1 to relate to longitude and PC2 to relate to the latitude of the country.

5. Contribution of each variable to the Principal Component Variation

  • This quantification is achieved with the square cosine

  • We use the fviz_cos2() function

  • Low value means the variable is not perfectly represented by the component.

  • High value means a good representation of the value on the component.

5.1. Representation of each region in PC1

fviz_cos2(data.pca.covid19, choice = "var", axes = 1)

5.2. Representation of each region in PC2

fviz_cos2(data.pca.covid19, choice = "var", axes = 2)

5.3. Representation of each region in PC1 and PC2

fviz_cos2(data.pca.covid19, choice = "var", axes = 1:2)

5.4. Biplot combined with cos2

fviz_pca_var(data.pca.covid19, col.var = "cos2",
            gradient.cols = c("black", "orange", "green"),
            repel = TRUE)

  • From the biplot:
    • Argentina, Brazil, Italy, Germany and Switzerland have high cos2 attributes and are colored in green: these samples contribute the highest scores to PC1 and PC2.
    • France, Finland, Saudi Arabia, Morocco and Canada have mid cos2 attributes and are colored orange.
    • China, Bat and Taiwan have low cos2 and are colored black: these samples contribute the lowest to the variability of PC1 and PC2.
  • Compare to the square cosine, from above.
library("ggbiplot")
ggbiplot(data.pca.covid19)
